[normal]Transparency of and rep[bold]orting by commissioners to date[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]8.1
[normal]              
[normal]I inherited only half a team, mainly ex Police Authority staff, who did not appreciate how to be transparent in the way that elected officials should be. 
[normal]  
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]8.2
[normal]              
[normal]In addition, 
[normal]the electronic processes were
[normal] 
[normal]n
[normal]o
[normal]t there either
[normal] but this is now addressed
[normal].
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]8.3
[normal]              
[normal]But we have got there, and I am confident that 
[normal]I 
[normal]and the Force are now as transparent a
[normal]s we could be.  Indeed it was re
[normal]assuring that Bernard Rix (COPACC) stated that my office is one of the best at being transparent nationally. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Conclusion[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]9.1
[normal]              
[normal]I feel I have highlighted many positives in this submission, and I have highlighted blockages too.
[normal] 
[normal] I am surprised that your questioning has not focussed at all on public engagement, arguably the biggest part of a PCC
[normal]s role.  For democracy to be effective, it has to be visibly effective.  I attend a public forum every two weeks, hold PCC surgeries and I have recruited 
[normal]six voluntary advocates, who are my “eyes and ears” in various communities, including the older community and the Polish
[normal] communities
[normal].
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]9.2
[normal]              
[normal]There is so much more that the role of the PCC can achieve, given the time, the right resources and the opportunity.  I believe I make a difference and I will continue to work hard to keep the people of Dorset safe.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]9.3
[normal]              
[normal]To detail all of the work undertaken in the year is difficult within 3000 words and I am happy to expand on the areas above and other areas I am influencing by appearing before your Committee.
